##  OpenMRS-on-AWS Case Study

Letâ€™s put this in real terms.

Weâ€™ve built OpenMRS (an open-source electronic health record system) on AWS. We've documented:

- **Inherited AWS controls** (e.g., physical security, hypervisor patching)
- **System-specific controls** (e.g., MFA for admins, role-based access in OpenMRS)
- **Continuous Monitoring Plan** (e.g., weekly CloudTrail reviews, monthly vuln scans)

Now, imagine our **hospitalâ€™s CIO** is serving as the AO. During her review, she notices:

> "Youâ€™ve enabled MFA for adminsâ€”why not for clinicians accessing PHI daily?"

This prompts a healthy security discussion. Perhaps clinicians use shared terminals in a clinic and MFA isn't feasibleâ€”or maybe it *is*, and we revise our plan to include it.

The **AO is not a roadblock**â€”theyâ€™re a **partner in secure operations**. Their questions sharpen our implementation and ensure weâ€™ve closed gaps *before* going live.

